(11, 'Antiqua Sailing Week: April 23- 29', 'Antigua', '4', '23', '2022', '2022-04-23', '4', '29', '2022', '2022-04-29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '45', '47', '48', '34', '69', '51', 'Weekly', 'Changes', ' ', 'https://www.sailingweek.com', NULL, NULL, 'About Antiqua Sailing Week', NULL, 'Antigua Sailing Week started in 1968 when a group of friends and hoteliers got together to hold a regatta, (sail boat or yacht race). \n\nAntigua Hotel Association sponsored the very first Antigua Sailing Week which was held from the 8th through the 15th of June 1968. \n\nFestivities included a three-day ‘Lord Nelson Regatta’ with sailing yachts of up to 135-feet in length, power boat races, deep sea fishing and Sunfish sailing contests. There was also a two-day race among Antigua’s workboat fishermen whose boats had been freshly painted for the event.\n\nThe inaugural Antigua Sailing Week was such a huge success that it was repeated the following year with dates being moved up a week to May 31 through June 7, 1969. And so it went each following year, with new sponsors coming on board and the program of events growing and evolving.', 'Caribbean Sailing Events Inc.', 'Suite 102 Harbour Walk,', 'Dockyard Drive', 'English Harbour', NULL, 'AG', NULL, '(268) 725.6651', 'media@sailingweek.com', 'Media Relations', 'https://www.sailingweek.com/media/press-overview/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Yes', 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:22', '2021-01-17 16:50:22'),
(12, 'Bookmobile Day, Ntl.: April 6', 'United States', '4', '6', '2022', '2022-04-06', '4', '6', '2022', '2022-04-06', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '58', '13', '47', '12', '52', NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', 'Wednesday of Ntl Lib Week', 'http://www.ala.org/aboutala/bookmobileday', NULL, NULL, 'About National Bookmobile Day', NULL, 'The Wednesday of National Library Week in the U.S. is the National Bookmobile Day. \n\nBookmobiles bring libraries to rural and poor communities that do not have libraries.  This practice began in 19th Century England. Mary Titcomb is credited with creating bookmobiles in the United States in 1900. These were known as Biblioburros.  In 1912 the first motorized vehicle was used to transport the portable library. \n\nToday is a day to celebrate bookmobiles and the amazing service they give to communities across the country.', 'American Library Association', '50 East Huron Street', NULL, 'Chicago', 'IL', 'US', '60611-2795', '(800) 545.2433 ', 'ala@ala.org', 'Macey Morales\nMedia Relations Manager', 'http://www.ala.org/aboutala/contactus', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:22', '2021-01-17 16:50:22'),
