(74, 'Test Tube Baby, First (1978): July 23', 'Worldwide', '7', '23', '2023', '2023-07-23', '7', '23', '2023', '2023-07-23', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '9', '43', '40', '20', NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/ivf-baby-louise-brown-story-test-tube-world-first-40th-anniversary-a8455956.html', NULL, NULL, 'About the Anniversary of the Birth of the First Test Tube Baby', NULL, '45th Anniversary. Louise Brown was born in Manchester, England on July 23, 1978, the first child conceived through In Vitro Fertilization. As of today, more than 8 million people have been born world wide through this procedure and it has made the dream of children accessible to millions of families who could not conceive otherwise.', 'Historical Anniversary. No Sponsor. ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(75, 'Fannie Mae & Freddie Mac Bailout (2008): September 7', 'United States', '9', '7', '2023', '2023-09-07', '9', '7', '2023', '2023-09-07', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '18', '37', '52', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://money.cnn.com/2008/09/07/news/companies/fannie_freddie/index.htm', NULL, NULL, 'About the Fannie Mae & Freddie Mac Bailout Anniversary ', NULL, 'Today is the 15th anniversary of the Fannie Mae & Freddie Mac Bailout September 7, 2008. \n\nFannie Mae (Federal National Mortgage Association) and Freddie Mac (Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation), were placed into conservatorship by the FHFA  (Federal Housing Finance Agency). This drastic move was made with the intention of stabilizing the plummeting housing market in the US that would shortly lead to a worldwide major economic crisis. ', 'Historic Anniversary', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(76, 'Oktoberfest (DE): September 16 –October 3', 'Germany', '9', '16', '2023', '2023-09-16', '10', '3', '2023', '2023-10-03', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '12', '16', '69', NULL, NULL, 'Weekly', 'Changes', '3rd Wknd of September - 1st Sunday October. ', 'https://www.oktoberfesttours.travel/oktoberfest-munich-germany/', NULL, NULL, 'About Oktoberfest in Germany', NULL, 'Oktoberfest is the world\'s largest beer festival. This two-week event starts the third week of September and ends at the first week of October. However, if German Reunification Day occurs after the end of Oktoberfest, the dates can be extended. Every year, this celebration is attended by more than 6 million people. Apart from chugging beer, this festival showcases amusement rides and games. Traditional German food is served.\n\nThe first Oktoberfest was held October 12, 1810 to celebrate the wedding of Crown Prince Ludwig to Princess Therese of Saxony-Hildburghausen.', 'Oktoberfest', 'Datenwerk GmbH\nLudwigstr. 8', NULL, 'München', NULL, 'DE', '80539', '(+49)(0) 89 997.3830', 'info@datenwerk.de', 'General Information', 'http://www.oktoberfest.de/en/general/contact/657/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Yes', 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(77, 'Pastoral Care Week: October 22-28', 'Worldwide', '10', '22', '2023', '2023-10-22', '10', '28', '2023', '2023-10-28', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '38', '35', '10', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Weekly', 'Changes', NULL, 'http://www.pastoralcareweek.org/pastandfuturethemes.html', NULL, NULL, 'About National Pastoral Care Week', NULL, 'Organizations and institutions throughout the world will recognize the spiritual needs of those we serve and the spiritual care given through professional chaplaincy and pastoral counseling within our communities. Chaplains, pastoral care counselors, educators and care providers will share in this year’s theme, “Spiritual Resilience.”\n \nRegardless of spiritual, religious or cultural background, Pastoral Care Week celebrates those who provide spiritual support to others.  It is supported by the Coalition On Ministry In Specialized Settings Network:  The Network on Ministries in Specialized Settings, whose members provide care in specialized settings such as hospitals, prisons, businesses, industries, long-term care facilities, pastoral counseling centers, hospices, military settings, nursing homes, corporations, congregations of sisters, priests and brothers, schools and universities throughout the world. \n \nThis year’s theme, “Spiritual Resilience,” acknowledges the role of Chaplains and Pastoral Counselors to support the spiritual resilience or growth of it in those we serve.  Spiritual Resilience represents one’s ability to navigate through, or recover from, life’s most challenging moments.  Spiritual Resilience finds its roots in one’s sense of spirituality and related practices, religion or beliefs, values, and outlook.  It also represents the individual’s ability to gain, maintain or revise a sense of purpose and meaning, relationships, connections to the sacred, nature, and understanding of themselves and the world around them.  These traumatic life events and losses invite the professional who can nurture spiritual resiliency.  Pastoral/Spiritual Care week provides a unique opportunity to both have a conversation to address suffering related to loss and trauma and to seek opportunities for strengthening spiritual resilience amid them. \n \nMany institutions will celebrate Pastoral Care Week by honoring the work and gifts of pastoral/spiritual care givers locally and internationally, as well as the spiritual needs of those who serve.  Among the variety of celebrations will be hand-blessing ceremonies for health workers; open houses; poetry jams by clients; lecture series and luncheons.', 'COMISS Network', 'Pastoral Care Week', '16806 Windsor Park Drive', 'Lutz', 'FL', 'US', '33549', '(800) 318.3849', 'kballard@chmca.org ', 'General Information', 'http://www.pastoralcareweek.org/contactus.html', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(78, 'Green Week, Intl. (DE): January 19-28', 'Germany & Worldwide', '1', '19', '2024', '2024-01-19', '1', '28', '2024', '2024-01-28', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '15', '43', '46', '47', '68', '16', 'Weekly', 'Changes', NULL, 'https://www.gruenewoche.com/AboutIGWBerlin/InternationalGreenWeek/', NULL, NULL, 'About International Green Week', NULL, 'First run in 1926, International Green Week is a global forum on food, agriculture and sustainability. The conference includes 1,800 exhibitors with over 100,000 products from all over the world as well as technology products, horticultural machinery and techniques, gardening and household supplies. ', 'Messe Berlin GmbH', 'Messedamm 22', NULL, 'Berlin', NULL, 'DE', '14055', NULL, 'igw@messe-berlin.de', 'Lars Jaeger, Project Manager', 'https://www.gruenewoche.com/AboutIGWBerlin/InternationalGreenWeek/', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“360\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/ondCodtC6TY\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'https://www.facebook.com/internationalegruenewoche', 'http://twitter.com/gruenewoche', 'https://www.youtube.com/GrueneWoche', NULL, '0', NULL, 'Berlin', NULL, 'Yes', 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(79, 'Leap Day: February 29', 'Worldwide', '2', '29', '2024', '2024-02-29', '2', '29', '2024', '2024-02-29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '30', '12', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', NULL, 'https://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-5451921/10-things-didnt-know-Leap-Day-babies.html', NULL, NULL, 'About Leap Day', NULL, '\"February 24, 1592 Pope Gregory XIII established the Gregorian Calendar via a Pappel Bull, the primary calendar used in the world today and the calendar underlying international commerce. \n\nThe new calendar went into effect on October 4, 1582. It would not be until 1752 that it became the official calendar throughout most of Europe and the colonies. \n\nThe Julian Calendar, which the world was using, was created by Julius Cesar. It had a problem though. It wasn’t accurate. Every year it was off by 11.5 minutes. Over the course of centuries, 11 minutes per year can add up. The Julian Calendar has 13 fewer days than the Gregorian and doesn’t follow a complete solar rotation of the earth.\n\nThe Gregorian calendar addressed this issue and split time into two eras: before the birth of Jesus Christ (BC) and after the nativity (AD).  Of course non-Christian religions didn’t like this so they changed it to Before the Common Era and Common Era.  No matter what you call it, the demarcation point is still the same: the Birth of Jesus Christ.\n\nThe Julian Calendar is still used by Orthodox Christians as their religious calendar, which is why you’ll find two different celebrations of Easter and Christmas each year.  Other religions use their own calendars, most of which follow the movements of the sun, moon and/or stars.  These calendars are shorter than the Gregorian Calendar, which is now the international standard. \n\nThe oldest calendar in the world is the Byzantine Calendar, which has been marking time over the past 7,500+ years.\"', 'Statistical Event. No Sponsor. ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(80, 'Sadie Hawkins/Bachelor\'s Day: February 29*', 'Worldwide', '2', '29', '2024', '2024-02-29', '2', '29', '2024', '2024-02-29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '40', '50', '12', '27', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', 'Leap Years Only', 'http://lil-abner.com', NULL, NULL, 'About Sadie Hawkins / Bachelor\'s Day in Leap Years', NULL, 'Sadie Hawkins Day occurs annually in November.  However, during leap years, February 29th is also set aside as Sadie Hawkins or Bachelor\'s Day. \n\nAccording to tradition, unwed women can ask their intended to marry them on this day, foreign of social stigma. Of course, it doesn’t have to be that serious.  This day is often celebrated with dances and mixers in which women ask men out. Legends state that on this day in Leap Years, men are especially attracted to women who take control. For this reason it is sometimes referred to as Bachelor\'s Day.\n\nThe annual event is in commemoration of the holiday that was featured in Li’l Abner, an Al Capp comic strip. This also honors the Sadie Hawkins dance where boys are asked by girls. On this day, girls ask boys out to a dance or date. \n\nIn the comic strip Li’l Abner, Sadie Hawkins was the daughter of Hekzebiah Hawkins, one of the earliest settlers of Dogpatch. She was perpetually waiting for a suitor. When she was 35 and still a spinster, her father called all the unmarried men in the town to join the foot race, with marriage to Sadie as a consequence. However, Sadie had her eyes for Adam Olis. \n\nUnfortunately, Olis is already courting Theresa Richmand, the daughter of the largest potato farmer in Dogpatch. Because it was such a good idea, the spinsters of the town decided to make it a yearly event on the first Saturday of November landing or following the 9th.', 'Cultural Tradition. See Capp Ent. for topical info.', 'Capp Enterprises, Inc.', '477 Madison Avenue, 15th Floor', 'New York City', 'NY', 'US ', '10022', '(212) 754.6120', 'cappenterprises@lil-abner.com', 'Licensing ', 'http://lil-abner.com/licensing-images/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(81, 'Time Refund Day: February 29', 'United States', '2', '29', '2024', '2024-02-29', '2', '29', '2024', '2024-02-29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '18', '17', '26', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', 'Only in Leap Years', 'https://www.hrblock.com/tax-center/newsroom/filing/remote-tax-assistance/time-refund-day-2020/', NULL, NULL, 'About Time Refund Day', NULL, 'Every four years we get an extra day in the year known as Leap Day. HR Block, the tax preparation company designated this extra day as National Time Refund Day to encourage individuals to enjoy themselves, take back their time and to introduce its virtual tax service.', 'H&R Block', 'One H&R Block Way', NULL, 'Kansas City', 'MO', 'US', '64105', '(816) 854.4287', 'mediadesk@hrblock.com', 'Media Relations', 'https://www.hrblock.com/tax-center/newsroom-media-desk/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(82, 'Underlings Day, Intl.: February 29', 'Worldwide', '2', '29', '2024', '2024-02-29', '2', '29', '2024', '2024-02-29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '8', '59', '44', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', 'Only in Leap Years', 'https://www.facebook.com/International-Underlings-Day-Every-Year-on-February-29', NULL, NULL, 'About International Underlings Day', NULL, 'Most days, those not on top, be it economic or in the workplace, are made to know it. But once every four years on Leap Day, the Underlings of the world rejoice. This is our day! Today is the day to celebrate those whom contribute, carry the water, take the direction and basically support everything. On International Underlings Day, it is the Underlings who are on top!\n\nFirst held in 1984. ', 'Peter D. Morris', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'US', NULL, NULL, 'pdmorris@mail.com', 'Peter D. Morris', 'Traditional Source', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(83, 'Madrid Spain Train Bombing (2004): March 11', 'Spain', '3', '11', '2024', '2024-03-11', '3', '11', '2024', '2024-03-11', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '29', '16', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.cnn.com/2013/11/04/world/europe/spain-train-bombings-fast-facts/index.html', '5286_Madrid_Train_BombingF.png', '5286_Madrid_Train_BombingE.png', 'About the Madrid Train Bombing (ES)', NULL, 'This is the 20th Anniversary of the Madrid Train Bombings. There were three major terrorist attacks in the first five years of the twenty-first century that forever changed Western civilization, civil safety and privacy rights.  These were the September 11, 2001 attacks on New York and Washington DC; the July 7, 2005 London bombings; and today’s anniversary, the March 11, 2004 Madrid Commuter Train bombings.\n\nIn Spain 10 bombs exploded on four commuter trains almost simultaneously, killing 191 people and injuring more than 1,800 during the morning rush hour. This was and continues to be the deadliest terrorist attack in Spain’s history.', 'Historical Event, No Sponsor.', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/-GyFYP7nKWw\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/OULSZHY_a3s\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/OULSZHY_a3s\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/j5dUA5LepbY\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(84, 'Three Mile Island (1979): March 28', 'United States', '3', '28', '2024', '2024-03-28', '3', '28', '2024', '2024-03-28', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '43', '15', '52', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'www.nrc.gov', '6703_Three_Mile_IslandF.png', '6703_Three_Mile_IslandE.png', 'About the Three Mile Island Disaster', NULL, '45th Anniversary. March 28, 1979 is the day of the Three Mile Island Nuclear Plant Meltdown. It stands as the worst nuclear disaster on US soil to date. ', 'Historical Anniversary. See US Energy Administration for Details', 'U.S. Energy Information Administration', '1000 Independence Ave., SW', 'Washington', 'DC', 'US', '20585', '(202) 586.8800', 'nfoCtr@eia.gov', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.eia.gov/about/contact/', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/LIqe2d2LcJc\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/0J7kHfBBBmk\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/0J7kHfBBBmk\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/eGI7VymjSho\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(85, 'Columbine Massacre Anniversary (1999): April 20', 'United States', '4', '20', '2024', '2024-04-20', '4', '20', '2024', '2024-04-20', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '13', '29', '52', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'https://www.cnn.com/2013/09/18/us/columbine-high-school-shootings-fast-facts/index.html', NULL, NULL, 'About the Columbine Massacre Anniversary', NULL, 'On April 20, 1999 two students from Columbine High School in Littleton Colorado, entered the school, heavily armed and proceeded murder twelve of their classmates and a teacher. The two shooters then shot themselves. \n\nThe victims were:\n\nCassie Bernall, 17\nSteven Curnow, 14\nCorey DePooter, 17\nKelly Fleming, 16\nMatthew Kechter, 16\nDaniel Mauser, 15\nDaniel Rohrbough, 15\nWilliam \"Dave\" Sanders, 47\nRachel Scott, 17\nIsaiah Shoels, 18\nJohn Tomlin, 16\nLauren Townsend, 18\nKyle Velasquez, 16\n\nToday is the 25th anniversary of the massacre. The student survivors are now in their 40s. \n\nWhen did school shootings start?\n\nOn November 12, 1840, University of Virginia law student Joseph Semmes shot and killed his professor John Anthony Gardner Davis. That is the first known school shooting in the US. \n\nThe first known school shooting at an American K-12 school occurred in 1853. Teacher William Butler was murdered by former student Matthews F. Ward. Ward was \'defending\' his brother\'s honor after he had been disciplined the day before. \n\nUntil the 1960s, school shootings were usually individual disputes with 0-2 fatalities, like the above. This changed on August 1, 1966, when a gunman climbed onto the observation deck at the University of Texas at Austin. For the next 96-minutes, he picked people off as a sniper, killing 17 and wounding 31.\n  \nCanada experienced its Columbine ten years prior at École Polytechnique, where 14 women were killed. England saw 18 killed at Dunblane in 1996\n\nColumbine heightened awareness of school shootings in the United States. Since, school shootings have become more frequent in the United States, which leads the world in school shootings. Some of the worst school shootings in history include Beslan (RU), Sandy Hook (USA), Virginia Tech (USA), Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School (USA), Erfurt (DE), Winnenden (DE), Realengo, (BR), and the Azerbaijan State Oil Academy (AZ).\n\nThe two worst individual school shooting are:\n\nTaliban attack on the Army Public School in Peshawar, Pakistan on December 16, 2014. With guns and grenades they killed 145 people. \n\nAl-Shabaab attack on Garissa University College in Garissa, Kenya, April 3, 2015. 147 people were killed. \n\nHave School shootings increased?\n\nDuring the 1970s, there were 29 school shootings, the worst being Cal-State, Fullerton with seven dead and two injured. Between 1980 & 1989, there were 40 shootings at schools. In the 1990s there were 63, including Columbine. Between 2000 and 2009, another 60 school shootings occurred. \n\nBetween 2010 and June 2018, the number of school shootings in the United States had reached 165. At this writing, there is still 18 months to go in this decade. If the trend continues, school shootings will have increased more than 300% over the past ten years. ', 'Historical Anniversary. No Sponsor. ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(86, 'Final Four (US-GA): April 6-8', 'United States', '4', '6', '2024', '2024-04-06', '4', '8', '2024', '2024-04-08', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '45', '14', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', NULL, 'http://www.ncaa.com/march-madness', NULL, ' ', 'About the Basketball Final Four', NULL, 'The Final Four features the championship collegiate basketball teams of the four regional competitions: East, South, Midwest and West regions. \n\nThe Final Four is the playoff championships to determine which two teams will ultimately face each other for the National Championship game in April. It covers both the men and women’s basketball programs. This event is the culmination of a series of games known as “March Madness”.\n\nThe tournament, which currently features 68 teams in 4 brackets was created in 1939 by the  National Association of Basketball Coaches. Originally it was the idea of Ohio State University coach Harold Olsen.', 'The National Collegiate Athletic Association', '700 W. Washington Street', 'P.O. Box 6222', 'Indianapolis', 'IN', 'US', '46206-6222', '(317) 917.6117', 'http://twitter.com/ncaastacey', 'Stacey Osburn\nDirector of Public and Media Relations', 'http://www.ncaa.org/about/contact-ncaa', '<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/dmmWNPwMv7k\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/HEhv0KIHF4M\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/HEhv0KIHF4M\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/hor_Ey0d1XI\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, 'Georgia Institute of Technology, Mercedes-Benz Stadium', NULL, 'Yes', 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
