(97, 'Emergency Medical Services Week, Ntl.: May 18-24', 'United States', '5', '18', '2025', '2025-05-18', '5', '24', '2025', '2025-05-24', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '20', '8', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Weekly', 'Changes', 'Same as SM business week', 'https://www.acep.org/administration/ems-resources/emsweek/', NULL, NULL, 'About National Emergency Medical Services Week', NULL, 'National Emergency Medical Services Week brings together local communities and medical personnel to publicize safety and honor the dedication of those whom provide the day-to-day lifesaving services on medicine\'s frontline.', 'American College of Emergency Physicians', '1125 Executive Circle', ' ', ' Irving', 'TX', 'US', ' 75038-2522', '(972) 550.0911', 'pr@acep.org', 'Media Relations', 'https://www.acep.org/contactus/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(98, 'Gaza Freedom Flotilla Attack (2010): May 31', 'Worldwide', '5', '31', '2025', '2025-05-31', '5', '31', '2025', '2025-05-31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '29', '36', '59', '62', NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaza_flotilla_raid', NULL, NULL, 'About the Anniversary of the Gaza Freedom Flotilla Attack', NULL, 'Today is the 15th Anniversary of the Israeli navy’s attack on the Gaza Freedom Flotilla in 2010. \n\nThe Gaza flotilla raid was a military operation conducted by Israel against six civilian ships in international waters on the Mediterranean Sea. Nine activists are killed during the raid, eight Turkish and one American. \n\nThe flotilla was organized by the \"Free Gaza Movement\" and the Turkish Foundation for Human Rights and Freedoms and Humanitarian Relief (iHH). It was carrying humanitarian aid and construction materials to the besieged Gaza Strip which had been under complete Israeli blockade since 2007. \n\nInternational outrage over the incident was immediate and drastically shook the Turkey-Israel relations.  As of 2020, the Gaza Strip is still under complete military control of the Israeli military with limited movement of goods and people in or out. \n\nGaza Strip has been occupied and/or quarantined by the Israeli army since 1967.', 'Historic Anniversary. No Sponsor.', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(99, 'Mount Saint Helens Eruption (US-WA) (1980): May 18', 'United States', '5', '18', '2025', '2025-05-18', '5', '18', '2025', '2025-05-18', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '15', NULL, '52', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://pubs.usgs.gov/fs/2000/fs036-00', NULL, NULL, 'About the Anniversary of Mt. St. Helens Eruption', NULL, 'Today is the 45th anniversary of the May 18, 1980 eruption of Mt. St. Helens. This Plinian eruption was in the same category as the infamous Mt Vesuvius eruption of 79AD and ranked five on the Volcanic Explosivity Index. That index measures volcanos on a scale of 1-7. Seven would match the volcanic eruption 600,000 years ago that created the Yellowstone Caldera and covered over 100 cubed kilometers. By contrast, Mt. St. Helens blew out 1 cubed kilometers. \n\nThe blast cloud traveled as far as 17 miles northward from the volcano and the landslide traveled about 14 miles west down the North Fork Toutle River. \n\nPrevailing winds blew 520 million tons of ash eastward across the United States and caused complete darkness in Spokane, Washington, 250 miles from the volcano. Fifty-seven people lost their lives as a result of the eruption, in addition to over 7000 big game animals and around 12-million salmon. \n\nPersonal note from Laura:\nMy family had just moved to Portland, Oregon from the Silicon Valley in January of 1980, when in February and March, rumblings began to be heard on the mountain.  We traded earthquakes for volcanos it seemed. On May 18th, the mountain completely exploded. You could see the cloud from Seattle, Washington and Portland, Oregon.\n\nThat first major explosion blew east, rather than west where we lived. For weeks following it one could follow the ash cloud spread in a large funnel shape from its origin, over the Rockies and into the Dakotas.  The cloud was so large and dense in ash, it could be clearly seen from outer space. \n\nI remember my father loading us in the FIAT and taking us to the top of Skyline Drive, which runs along the hills separating where we lived from the city of Portland and the Willamette River.  It seemed to go on and on, as high as the eye could see. The mountain seemed to cough up billow after billow of gas and hot ash.  We’d never seen anything like it. The entire top of the mountain, we would later discover, had been blown off.\n\nOver the next several months the mountain continued to erupt, with the wind not always in our favor. One particular Saturday my parents held a garage sale.  When we walked outside, it looked like it was snowing.  It wasn’t. It was ash, falling from the sky and covering it in several inches of grey, flaky dusk. \n\nThat dust got into everything and when it rained, it turned into a thick paste.  We had to walk around for days with monkey masks (disposable medical masks), which as a young teen, I really hated. But, the air was too thick to breathe. One of the aspects I remember fondly was when my father allowed me to help him take apart the engine of the FIAT and clean it. Every part was caked in ash dust. Thank heaven it wasn’t as complicated as today’s engines. It had a manual choke, and no radio.  It was a great learning experience and a great father-daughter project.  Little did I know in a few years, that car would be mine.\n\nFor those of us who witnessed Mount Saint Helens and her eruption, it is something we’ll never forget. For us, far away, it was curiosity.  For those close, fifty-seven people lost their lives. Most from inhaling scalding ash. \n\nRound about the 25th anniversary I found myself in Oregon again.  Now in my thirties, I drove my car up to the mountain, which was again open. The forest was beginning to come back.  Animals had returned and for a moment it was difficult to believe the event ever happened. Until, one glanced skyward and saw. A crater where a rounded dome once stood, a mountain top shaved. \n\nOh yes, now, I remember. I remember well.', 'Historic Anniversary. No Sponsor.', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(100, 'US Open Golf Championship (US-PA): June 12-15', 'United States', '6', '12', '2025', '2025-06-12', '6', '15', '2025', '2025-06-15', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '45', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Weekly', 'Changes', NULL, 'http://www.usga.org', NULL, NULL, 'About the US Open Golf Championship', NULL, 'The US Open Golf Championship is sponsored by the United States Golf Association, and is often held on the third Sunday of June. The event is one of the four major golf tournaments in the world. ', 'United States Golf Association', '77 Liberty Corner Rd', NULL, 'Far Hills', 'NJ', 'US', '7931', '(908) 234.2300', 'http://www.usga.org/contact-us.html', 'General Information', 'http://www.usga.org/contact-us.html', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, 'Oakmont Country Club, Oakmont, PA', NULL, 'Yes', 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(101, 'Hurricane Katrina 20th Anniversary (2005): August 29', 'United States', '8', '29', '2025', '2025-08-29', '8', '29', '2025', '2025-08-29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '15', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://katrinadestruction.com/', NULL, NULL, 'About the 20th Anniversary of Katrina ', NULL, 'This is the 20th Anniversary of Hurricane Katrina. \n\nOn August 29, 2005, Hurricane Katrina pounced upon southeastern Louisiana and southern Mississippi. As a Category 4 storm, the devastation was unimaginable and Katrina became one of the deadliest hurricanes ever to hit the United States. An estimated 1,833 people died and millions of others were left injured or homeless all along the Gulf Coast and in New Orleans.\n\nAccording to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), Katrina caused around $108 billion in damage and ranked sixth in strength of all recorded Atlantic hurricanes. It wasn\'t only a strong storm; it was also a large one. With winds stretching 25 to 30 nautical miles and an extremely wide swath, the winds extended at least 75 nautical miles to the east from the storm\'s center.', 'Historical Anniversary. No Sponsor.', 'Hurricane Katrina Destruction', '1805 Higley AVE SE', 'Cedar Rapids', 'IA', 'US', '52403', '(815) 670.5861', 'http://katrinadestruction.com/contact/', 'General Information', 'http://katrinadestruction.com/contact/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(102, 'RMS Titanic Located (1985): September 1', 'Worldwide', '9', '1', '2025', '2025-09-01', '9', '1', '2025', '2025-09-01', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '47', '48', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.titanicuniverse.com/titanic-wreck', NULL, NULL, 'About the Anniversary of the Discovery of the RMS Titanic', NULL, 'Today is the 40th Anniversary of the discovery of the RMS Titanic wreckage. It was on September 1, 1985 that the wreckage of RMS Titanic was located about 600 km south-southeast of Newfoundland under 3,800 meters of ocean. Discovered by a French-American expedition team spearheaded by Jean Louis Michel and Robert Ballard, the key to finding the Titanic was a remote-controlled machine called Argo. \n\nThe wreckage has two main parts about 600 meters apart. The stern has deteriorated, but still recognizable. The midsection of the ship broke and scattered across the seabed The debris plane is littered with personal belongings of passengers, furniture and machinery from the ship. The bow remains relatively intact.\n\nPrior to this discover, there were numerous attempts to locate the famous wreck. Though located, attempts to bring it to the surface have been unsuccessful due to the advanced fragility of the remains.', 'Historical Anniversary. No Sponsor.  No Sponsor.', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(103, 'Statistics Day, World: October 20', 'Worldwide', '10', '20', '2025', '2025-10-20', '10', '20', '2025', '2025-10-20', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '43', '13', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', 'Next in 2025', 'https://worldstatisticsday.org', NULL, NULL, 'About World Statistics Day', NULL, 'World Statistics Day occurs every five years on October 20th. The 2020 event will be its third incarnation. Statistics are key to understanding trends, the direction of populations and where resources should be allocated. They help us make sense of information by partitioning it into bite size pieces. Statistics are the key to informed decision-making. World Statistics Day is created by the United Nations in an effort to educate the public on the importance of statistics and the need to continue to develop sound methods, new technology and systems to produce, analyze and distribute them.  ', 'United Nations Human Settlements Programme ', 'United Nations Avenue, Gigiri ', ' P.O. Box 30030, 00100 ', 'Nairobi', NULL, 'KE', ' ', NULL, 'advocacy@unhabitat.org', 'Media Liaison', 'http://www.urbanoctober.org/2017/global.asp?pcd=3', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“360\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/fhdM21AZwPg\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(104, 'Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Meltdown (JP) (2011): March 11', 'Japan', '3', '11', '2026', '2026-03-11', '3', '11', '2026', '2026-03-11', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '15', '36', '61', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.gregpalast.com/fukushima-they-knew/#more-6471', NULL, NULL, 'About the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Meltdown in Japan ', NULL, 'Today is the 15th Anniversary of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Meltdown, March 11, 2011. \n\nThe nuclear disaster occurred when the plant was hit by a tsunami triggered by one of the world’s most deadly earthquakes, a magnitude 9.0. Radioactive material began releasing the next day. The cleanup is expected to take decades. Some contaminated water has even made it to the sea, affecting fish and plant life. More than 300,000 people evacuated the area due to the tsunami and earthquake. \n\nThe nuclear disaster was found to be manmade and that the plant was unable to weather such a disaster.\n \nThe first three of their six reactors melted own in MARCH 2011 damaging the fourth reactor. Decommissioning could take more than 40 years. Nuclear refugees total over 71,000 sadly remaining in temporary housing.', 'Historical Event, No Sponsor.', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
(105, 'Tohoku Earthquake & Tsunami Anniversary (JP) (2011): March 11', 'Japan', '3', '11', '2026', '2026-03-11', '3', '11', '2026', '2026-03-11', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '15', '61', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.huffingtonpost.com/news/japan-earthquake-anniversary/', NULL, NULL, 'About the Anniversary of the Tohoku Earthquake & Tsunami in Japan', NULL, 'Today is the 15th anniversary of the Tohoku Earthquake & Tsunami in Japan which occurred Friday March 11, 2011. The magnitude 9.0 undersea earthquake, was the biggest earthquake in Japan’s history, and fourth most powerful of the modern age. \n\nThis deadly earthquake followed by a Tsunami claimed over 16,000 lives. Hundreds of thousands of building were damaged, half of which collapsed or were totally destroyed. Millions were left without electricity. ', 'Historical Event, No Sponsor.', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', ' ', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Approved', '2021-01-17 16:50:23', '2021-01-17 16:50:23'),
