(170, '55-MPH Speed Limit Day (1974): January 2', 'United States', '1', '2', '2020', '2020-01-02', '1', '2', '2020', '2020-01-02', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '47', '25', '52', NULL, ' ', 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/nixon-signs-national-speed-limit-into-law', '3264_55_MPH_DayF.jpg', '3264_55_MPH_DayE.jpg', 'About 55 Mile Per Hour Day', NULL, 'Today is the anniversary of the enactment of the 55 mile per hour speed limit in the United States in 1974.\n\nSpeed limits have been with us since 1757, the first of which was passed in Boston. The 55 mile per hour speed limit became the maximum speed limit in the United States for a period of 12 years beginning in 1974 and ending in 1986. It was thought to force fuel economy and came into being after the 1973 oil embargo.  Experts believed the law would force fuel consumption to fall by 2.2%. In reality it only fell between .5 and 1.1%, depending upon the study.\n\nAs Sammy Hagar famously states in his song “I Can’t Drive 55” (see below), the double nickel speed limit was not popular, especial on rural highways in western states. In 1987 the US Congress raised the national speed limit to 65 MPH. By the end of 1995, National Highway Designation Act permanently killed the idea of a national speed limit, transferring authority to the individual States.\n\nWe’ve included a few fast songs from the era for your enjoyment below.', 'Historical Anniversary. See: U.S. General Services Administration', 'Office of Citizen Services and Innovative Technologies', '1800 F Street, NW', 'Washington', 'DC', 'US', '20405', '(800) 333.4636', 'http://answers.usa.gov/system/templates/selfservice/USAGov/#!portal/1012/email_us', 'Citizen Services', 'http://www.usa.gov/Contact-Us.shtml', '<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/RvV3nn_de2k\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/4tcXblWojdM\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '<iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/l039y9FaIjc\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(171, 'Adopt a Rescued Bird Month: January', 'United States', '1', '1', '2020', '2020-01-01', '1', '31', '2020', '2020-01-31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', '26', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Monthly', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.pethealthnetwork.com/all-pet-health/bird-health-care/january-national-adopt-a-rescued-bird-month', NULL, NULL, 'About Adopt a Rescued Bird Month', NULL, 'If you live in West Los Angeles, you may have seen the flock of green parrots that lives there. Conventional wisdom is a few birds escaped from a pet store fire sometime in the 1980s and now they number in the 100s. It’s quite a sight the first time you see them. Parrots are not native to North America, but exotic birds are popular pets and sometimes they get lost, their owners pass away or their owners are forced to give them up. This means they end up in shelters and need to find new homes. Adopt a Rescue Bird Month came about to highlight the fact that animal rescue helps all types of animals, including birds. If your dream is to own a bird, before you purchase from a pet store, check with your local shelter and bird rescue. You just might be able to give a bird the forever home it’s been waiting for!', 'Unofficial Event. No Sponsor.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
