(243, 'Cheese Lover\'s Day: January 20', 'United States', '1', '20', '2020', '2020-01-20', '1', '20', '2020', '2020-01-20', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '19', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.foxnews.com/food-drink/2018/01/20/national-cheese-lovers-day-celebrations-sweep-internet.html', NULL, NULL, 'About National Cheese Lover\'s Day', NULL, 'Cheese Lover\'s Day celebrates cheese. \n\nCheese appears to be one of those foods that no one quite knows where it came from.  All regions of the world have it. It can be made out of milk from any animal.  The legend is that an Arabian traveler accidentally created it when he stored milk in a sheep’s stomach pouch. It separated into curds and whey and he decided he liked it. From Arabia it spread to Europe.  From Europe, it traveled with the pilgrims to the New World. \n\nToday 1/3 of the milk produced in the US each year goes to create cheese. \n\nThis is an unofficial holiday with no sponsor. ', 'Unofficial Event. No Sponsor. See American Dairy Association on topic.', 'American Dairy Association', '325 Chestnut Street, Suite 600', 'Philadelphia', 'PA', 'US', '19106', '(312) 240.2880', 'http://www.nationaldairycouncil.org/AboutNDC/Pages/ContactUs.aspx', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.nationaldairycouncil.org/AboutNDC/Pages/ContactUs.aspx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(244, 'Cheesy Sock Day, Ntl.: January 21', 'United States', '1', '21', '2020', '2020-01-21', '1', '21', '2020', '2020-01-21', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '9', '59', '11', '52', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'https://www.fillaheart4kids.org', NULL, NULL, 'About National Cheesy Sock Day™', NULL, 'Whimsical warm socks, cheesy popcorn, toiletries and a funny note of support and encouragement, this is what a Cheesy Sock Day care package includes. Its purpose is to raise awareness of the plight of homeless, unaccompanied minors and children in foster care, many of whom lack the most basic necessities (like warm, clean socks), to make it through the winter. ', 'Fill a Heart 4 Kids', '400 E Illinois Rd.', NULL, 'Lake Forest', 'IL', 'US', '60045', NULL, 'info@fillaheart4kids.org', 'General Information', 'https://www.fillaheart4kids.org/contact', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(245, 'Child Inventor\'s Day (1706): January 17', 'Worldwide', '1', '17', '2020', '2020-01-17', '1', '17', '2020', '2020-01-17', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '9', '43', '46', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.ushistory.org/franklin/info/index.htm', NULL, NULL, 'About Child Inventor\'s Day Celebrating Benjamin Franklin', NULL, 'Child Inventor’s Day marks the anniversary of Benjamin Franklin’s birth January 17, 1706. Franklin completed his first invention at the age of 11 in 1717, (a set of swimming fins for the hands). \n\nBy the age of 17, Franklin became a publisher and would go on to become one of the founders of the United States, a prolific writer and inventor. \n\nOn this day children are encouraged to reach for their dreams by experimenting, trying new ideas and looking at things in a different way.', 'Historical Anniversary. See the Benjamin Franklin Museum for History', 'Benjamin Franklin Museum', 'Independence National Historical Park\n143 South Third Street', 'Philadelphia', 'PA', 'US', '19106', '(215) 965.2305', 'http://www.nps.gov/common/utilities/sendmail/sendemail.cfm', 'General Information', 'http://www.nps.gov/inde/contacts.htm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(246, 'Child-centered Divorce Awareness Month, Intl.: January', 'Worldwide', '1', '1', '2020', '2020-01-01', '1', '31', '2020', '2020-01-31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '9', '17', '25', '40', '26', NULL, 'Monthly', 'Same', NULL, 'https://divorcedparentsupport.com', NULL, NULL, 'About International Child-centered Divorce Awareness Month', NULL, 'If you’re a parent coping with divorce-related issues, professionals around the world are here to provide free products and services to you all through January. In recognition of International Child-Centered Divorce Month, we’ve enrolled child-centered divorce attorneys, mediators, divorce coaches, therapists, financial planners and other professionals on four continents to join this educational campaign. Their goal is to share insights, advice, tips and tools to help you create the most positive outcome for your family as you transition through divorce and beyond.\n', 'Rosalind Sedacca', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FL', 'US', NULL, '(561) 385.4205', 'rosalind@childcentereddivorce.com', 'Rosalind Sedacca', 'Traditional Source', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(247, 'Children Impacted by a Parents Cancer Month: January', 'United States', '1', '1', '2020', '2020-01-01', '1', '31', '2020', '2020-01-31', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '9', '20', '17', '52', NULL, NULL, 'Monthly', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.campkesem.org', NULL, NULL, 'About Children Impacted by a Parents Cancer Month', NULL, 'First run in 2000, Children Impacted by a Parent\'s Cancer Month seeks to support children and families where one or more parent is undergoing cancer treatment, living in remission or has died. The impact this has on a young life can be devastating, leading to isolation, lower academic scores and a loss of childhood.  Resources are available to help children and families cope. Outreach during the month serves families, schools, health care and mental health professionals.', 'Camp Kesem', 'PO Box 164', NULL, 'Winnetka', 'IL', 'US', '60093', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(248, 'Chinese New Year (Rat) (CN): January 25', 'China', '1', '25', '2020', '2020-01-25', '1', '25', '2020', '2020-01-25', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '12', '31', '61', '2', '69', NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', 'new moon between 21 January and 20 February', 'http://www.travelchinaguide.com/essential/holidays/spring-festival.htm', 'Chinese_New_YearF.jpg', 'Chinese_New_YearE.jpg', 'About the Chinese New Year', NULL, 'Chinese New Year is a big holiday in China and with Chinese communities worldwide. It is treated much like Christmas in the West or the Eid holidays in the Islamic world. Festivities last 15 days and are now known as the Spring Festival in China. \n\nGifts are exchanged and red packets with money in even number denominations. Families travel far and wide to be together, special foods are prepared with the night before the Chinese New Year. This meal is the most important and is referred to as the ‘reunion dinner’.  \n\nRetailers have many specials leading up to and during the festivities. \n\nActivities culminate on the 15th day with the Lantern Festival, marking the end of the annual Chinese New Year Celebration. \n\nFor any business doing business with China, basically lock out the week leading up to it and the 15 days of. You’ll have a hard time getting anyone to pay much attention to business. This time is about celebrating.\n\nChinese companies typically shut down for the two weeks of Chinese New Year.', 'Chinese Cultural Event. See the Museum of Chinese in America for information', '215 Centre Street', ' ', 'New York City', 'NY', 'US', '10013', '(212) 619.4785', 'press@mocanyc.org', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.mocanyc.org/about/contact', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(249, 'Chinese Year of the Rat 4718: January 25, 2020 - February 11, 2021', 'China', '1', '25', '2020', '2020-01-25', '2', '11', '2021', '2021-02-11', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '12', '31', '61', '2', NULL, NULL, 'Annual', 'Changes', 'new moon between 21 January and 20 February', 'http://www.history.com/topics/holidays/chinese-new-year', NULL, NULL, 'About Chinese year of the Rat 4718', NULL, 'The Chinese Calendar is the backdrop of the Chinese year and is based upon the phases of the moon and runs in 12 year cycles, each year denoting a different animal in the Chinese Astrological Lineup.  This year is the Year of the Rat. If the Chinese year were numbered, this year would be 4718. \n', 'Chinese Cultural Event. See the Museum of Chinese in America for information', '215 Centre Street', ' ', 'New York City', 'NY', 'US', '10013', '(212) 619.4785', 'press@mocanyc.org', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.mocanyc.org/about/contact', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(250, 'Chocolate Cake Day: January 27', 'United States', '1', '27', '2020', '2020-01-27', '1', '27', '2020', '2020-01-27', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '19', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, ' ', 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'https://www.theodysseyonline.com/8-reasons-national-chocolate-cake-day-day', NULL, NULL, 'About National Chocolate Cake Day', NULL, 'Love chocolate cake? Then you have James Baker to thanks. \n\nBaker invented chocolate as we know it today, that is, in a form that could easily be cooked.  In 1764 Mr. Baker placed beans between millstones and ground them down to dust.  This powder could then be mixed with liquids or solids to change the flavor, the same way you add salt or other seasonings.  However, this process was quite expensive, so only the wealthiest people could afford it.  By the early nineteenth century (1828) Conrad Van Houten developed a method for extracting the cacao liquor from the fat in the cocoa bean.  This made chocolate an affordable ingredient and its popularity took off. \n\nDevil’s Food cake by the Pittsburgh based Duff Company was the first chocolate cake mix. However, WWII got in the way and at the end of the war Duncan Hines and General Mills burst on the scene with their mixes and took nearly half the market between them. \n\nBy the millennium, artisan chocolate cakes, those without flour and closer to the consistency of fudge brownies with less sugar became the rage. \n\nHowever you like your chocolate cake, today is the day to enjoy it.  Indulge!', 'Unofficial Event. No Sponsor.  See Cordon Bleu Culinary School for info', 'Cordon Bleu', '8 Rue Léon Delhomme', 'Paris', NULL, 'FR', '75015', '(+33)(1) 53.68.22.50', 'mwarren@cordonbleu.edu', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.cordonbleuusa.com/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(251, 'Chocolate Covered Cherry Day, Ntl.: January 3', 'United States', '1', '3', '2020', '2020-01-03', '1', '3', '2020', '2020-01-03', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '19', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, ' ', 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'https://www.candyfavorites.com/blog/a-history-of-cherry-cordials-for-valentines-day/', NULL, NULL, 'About National Chocolate Covered Cherry Day', NULL, 'Chocolate Covered Cherry Day celebrates the cordial of cherries covered in chocolate.\n\nThe idea of covering fruits, nuts and even nougat with chocolate wasn’t really possible until the 19th Century. The technology needed to separate the chocolate from cocoa butter wouldn’t be invented until 1828 by Conrad Van Houten in today’s Netherlands. Without this process, chocolate could only be used as a spice, much the same way you would use cinnamon or ginger.\n\nFortunately, the process was developed and further techniques, including conching, invented by Rudolph Lindt in 1879 would eventually lead to that box of chocolates everyone loves to get. \n\nChocolate Covered Cherry Day is an unofficial holiday with no sponsor.', 'Unofficial Event. No Sponsor. See Fine Chocolate Industry Association for info/details', 'Fine Chocolate Industry Association', '4701 SW Admiral Way #324', 'Seattle', 'WA', 'US', '98116', '(206) 577.9983', 'info@finechocolateindustry.org', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.finechocolateindustry.org/ballyhoo', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(252, 'Christian Unity Week, Intl. (Northern Hemisphere): January 18-25', 'Northern Hemisphere', '1', '18', '2020', '2020-01-18', '1', '25', '2020', '2020-01-25', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '10', '38', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Weekly', 'Same', 'Feast of Saint Peter and the conversion of Saint Paul.', 'http://www.oikoumene.org/en/press-centre/events/week-of-prayer-for-christian-unity', NULL, NULL, 'About International Christian Unity Week', NULL, 'At least once a year (January in the Northern Hemisphere, June in the Southern Hemisphere), Christians are reminded of Jesus’ prayer for his disciples that “they may be one so that the world may believe” (see John 17.21). Hearts are touched and Christians come together to pray for their unity. Congregations and parishes all over the world exchange preachers or arrange special ecumenical celebrations and prayer services. The event that touches off this special experience is the Week of Prayer for Christian Unity.\n\nTraditionally the week of prayer is celebrated between 18-25 January, between the feasts of St Peter and St Paul. In the southern hemisphere, where January is a vacation time, churches often find other days to celebrate it, for example around Pentecost, which is also a symbolic date for unity.', 'World Council of Churches', 'Ecumenical Centre', '1 Route des Morillons', 'Le Grand-Saconnex ', ' ', 'CH', '1218', '(+41) 79 507.6363', 'mej@wcc-coe.org', 'Marianne Ejdersten, WCC Communications Director ', 'http://ncca.org/contact-us.aspx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(253, 'Christmas, Orthodox (C): January 7', 'Worldwide', '1', '7', '2020', '2020-01-07', '1', '7', '2020', '2020-01-07', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '10', '38', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', NULL, 'https://www.thesun.co.uk/fabulous/5258712/orthodox-christians-christmas-day-january-7/', NULL, NULL, 'About the Orthodox Christian Holiday of Christmas', NULL, 'Orthodox Christmas is celebrated by various Orthodox Christian faiths in countries including Russia, Serbia, Bulgaria, Greece and Macedonia. ', 'Christian Religious Event. See Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America for info', 'Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America', '8 East 79th Street', 'New York City', 'NY', 'US', '10075', '(212) 570.3500', 'http://www.goarch.org/archdiocese/contact/archdiocese_contact_form', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.goarch.org/archdiocese/contact', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(254, 'Cigarettes Are Hazardous To Your Health Day (1964): January 11', 'Worldwide', '1', '11', '2020', '2020-01-11', '1', '11', '2020', '2020-01-11', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '1', '20', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/ps/retrieve/Narrative/NN/p-nid/60', NULL, NULL, 'About National Cigarettes Are Hazardous To Your Health Day', NULL, 'Cigarettes Are Hazardous To Your Health Day marks the anniversary of Surgeon General Luther L. Terry\'s issuance of a report on January 11, 1964 that declared cigarettes to be hazardous to health. In his own words, the report \"hit the country like a bombshell,\" making it the lead story and front page on news sources worldwide.\n\nThe anniversary of this event is set aside to continue to raise awareness on the dangers of smoking cigarettes for the smoker and for those around him or her.', 'Historical Anniversary. See National Institute of Health for History', 'Clinical Center Office of Communications', '10 Cloister Court, Building 61, Room 100', 'Bethesda', 'MD', 'US', '20892', '(301) 496.2563', ' ', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.nih.gov/about/visitor/index.htm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(255, 'Citizen United Decision by Supreme Court (2010): January 21', 'United States', '1', '21', '2020', '2020-01-21', '1', '21', '2020', '2020-01-21', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '36', '18', '25', '52', ' ', 'Daily', 'Same', ' ', 'http://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/citizens-united-v-federal-election-commission/', NULL, NULL, 'About the Anniversary of the Citizen United Decision  by Supreme Court in 2012', NULL, 'Today is the 10th anniversary of the landmark Citizens United decision, which was upheld by the US Supreme Court in 2010. \n\nThe court stated, in 2010 that corporations, like people, have a constitutional right to be heard in election campaigns and that there should be no limit to the amount of money corporations and unions can spend in elections, as long as the money is independent of the campaign it intends to support.\n\nThis decision has flooded national and local elections in the United States with billions of dollars from special interests groups, creating an atmosphere of competing messages and non-transparent agenda funding.', 'Historical Anniversary. See the US Supreme Court', 'Supreme Court of the United States', '1 First Street, NE', 'Washington', 'DC', 'US', '20543', '(202) 479.3211  Reporters press 1', ' ', 'Media Relations', 'https://www.supremecourt.gov/contact/contactus.aspx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(256, 'Clam Chowder Day, New England Style: January 21*', 'United States', '1', '21', '2020', '2020-01-21', '1', '21', '2020', '2020-01-21', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '19', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.narragansettbeer.com/recipe/national-new-england-clam-chowder-day?age-verified=19e09aef05', NULL, NULL, 'About National New England Clam Chowder Day', NULL, 'This is one of two unofficial events celebrating clam chowder. The other is in February 25. Their are several varieties of clam chowder, the most common being  New England (white sauce), Manhattan (red sauce) and Rhode Island Clam Chowder (clear broth).\n\nChowder is a cross between a stew and a soup, essentially made of vegetables and fish stewed in a cauldron. Calderia is Latin for a “place for warming things.” Jowter is old English for a “fish peddler”. It is believed that this is the origin of the word chowder. The first recipes for chowder seem originate in both France and England, among the coastal fishing villages. The custom was to have a cauldron of simmering in the house, awaiting the fishing ships return to port. A portion of each man’s catch would be tossed in and the resulting chowder was served to the community to celebrate the safe return of the ship.\n\nClams were an easy choice, and could be gathered without the need to go out in a ship. This made them ideal for chowder, especially when the weather was bad. Of course clams could only be harvested at certain times of the year, so the chowder was often made from haddock, cod or other local fish. Chowder was a staple of the working classes.\n\nLater recipes for chowder included other meats like ham, bacon and poultry. Clam chowder became a favorite with East Coast Americans, especially on Fridays due to a Christian custom of only eating fish on Friday.', 'Unofficial Event. No Sponsor. See the Maine Clammers Assoc. on topic. ', 'Maine Clammers Association ', 'PO Box 26', 'Freeport', 'ME', 'US', '4032', '(207) 615.5640', 'maineclammers@comcast.com', 'Media Relations', 'http://maineclammers.org/about/contact-us/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(257, 'Clean Off Your Desk Day, Ntl.: January 13', 'United States', '1', '13', '2020', '2020-01-13', '1', '13', '2020', '2020-01-13', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '8', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', '2nd Monday  of January', 'http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2012/01/09/clean-desk-day_n_1167886.html', NULL, NULL, 'Clean Off Your Desk Day, Ntl.: January 13', NULL, 'National Clean Off Your Desk Day is set aside each year to encourage people to organize their desks and office space. How many mystery piles do you have? When was the last time you saw the bottom of a drawer? Has your inbox ever gone down, or does it keep growing and growing?\n\nThese are all signs that it is time to clean off your desk. And now, you have a holiday as an excuse on the second Monday of January each year.  Get to it!\n\nCreated by AC Vierow of Clio, Michigan, whom also founded International Goof-off Day in March, Blame Someone Else Day and National Boss-Employee Exchange Day. ', 'AC Vierow', 'Box 71', '5091 Farrand Rd', 'Clio', 'MI', 'US', '48420', '(810) 687.0423', ' ', 'AC Vierow', 'Traditional Source', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
