(267, 'Confederate Heroes Day (US-TX)(1807): January 19*', 'United States', '1', '19', '2020', '2020-01-19', '1', '19', '2020', '2020-01-19', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '3', '29', '59', '36', '52', NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.hr.sao.texas.gov/compensation/Holidays2016_2017.pdf', NULL, NULL, 'About the Confederate Memorial Day in Texas', NULL, 'Confederate Memorial Day is celebrated in most of the former states of The Confederacy on different days of the year. In some cases like Georgia, it is no longer referred to as Confederate Memorial Day, rather as \'state holiday\'. It is an official state holiday in most and honors the men who died fighting for The Confederacy during the American Civil War, 1861-1865. \n\nDates are as follows: \n\nAlabama, Georgia: 4th Monday in April \n\nMississippi: Last Monday in April\n\nFlorida: April 26; \n\nTennessee, Kentucky & Louisiana: June 3, Jefferson Davis\'s birthday 1808\n\nNorth & South Carolina: May 10, Anniversary of the death of General \"Stonewall\" Jackson in 1863\n\nTexas: January 19, Birthday of Robert E. Lee 1807; \n\nDue to the 400 year legacy of slavery (ending in 1865) and state supported racial segregation (ending in 1964), this event is highly contentious and seen as a celebration of racism by many critics. Detractors insist this plays into existing racism and celebrates white supremacy and slavery.\n\nProponents for the observance month insist that the Confederacy played a part in shaping who we are and the ramifications as well as contributions continue today. To deny a portion of our past, good and bad, is selective censorship. This month can also be used to explore the unspoken but oft felt prejudices and perceived reality that political correctness squelches. \n\nWhether you side with the detractors or the proponents, the best way to acknowledge this month is to spend some time reading the actual Constitution of the United States and learning history. History, not social studies. A great place to start is with Howard Zinn’s Peoples’ History of the United States, which some states, including Arizona, have tried to ban from their schools.  Why? Because it is a history of the American people, not the leaders and looks at the nation from the perspective of the 99%, the immigrants, migrant workers, women, religious minorities, slaves, the common man.\"', 'Historical Anniversary. See State of Texas', 'State Auditors Office', '1501 N Congress Ave', 'Austin', 'TX', 'US', '78701', '(512) 936.9500', 'auditor@sao.state.tx.us', 'General Information', 'http://www.texas.gov/', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(268, 'Cordova Iceworm Festival (US-AK): January 25 - February 1', 'United States', '1', '25', '2020', '2020-01-25', '2', '1', '2020', '2020-02-01', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', '14', '69', '52', NULL, NULL, 'Weekly', 'Changes', NULL, 'https://www.icewormfestival.com', '4056_Cordova_Ice_Worm_DayF.png', '4056_Cordova_Ice_Worm_DayE.png', 'About Cordova Iceworm Festival', NULL, 'Throughout the glaciers and ice in northern climates, worms thrive. They\'re an essential part of the ecosystem and actually enjoy being frozen. \n\nEach year over the first weekend of February the city of Cordova Alaska hosts the Cordova Iceworm Festival to welcome the little worms first emergence prior to the spring thaw. \n\nThe tradition started with a single day event in 1961 and festivities today cover an entire week.', 'Cordova Chamber of Commerce', '404 1st Street', 'PO Box 99', 'Cordova', 'AK', 'US', '99574', '(907) 424.7260', 'visitcordova@ak.net', 'Media Relations', 'http://cordovachamber.com/contact-us', '<iframe width=“640\" height=“480\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/0H31QrUqIfQ\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Yes', 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
(269, 'Corn Chip Day, Ntl.: January 29', 'United States', '1', '29', '2020', '2020-01-29', '1', '29', '2020', '2020-01-29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '19', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'https://www.fritolay.com/get-to-know-us/company', NULL, NULL, 'About National Corn Chip Day', NULL, 'National Corn Chip Day is a day to acknowledge and honor fried or baked cornmeal, divided into bite-sized pieces, usually sold in bags and eaten either alone or with a dip. \n\nSince 1932, people have been indulging in corn chips. It started when C.E. \"Elmer\" Doolin bought a bag of fried corn chips and realized he\'d discovered gold. Doolin sold his mother\'s wedding ring and purchased the recipe. He immediately began manufacturing them under the name \'Frito\'. \n\nEver since that day, we\'ve been enjoying corn chips.', 'Unofficial Event. No Sponsor.  See Frito Lay for History', 'Frito Lay', '7701 Legacy Dr. ', 'Plano', 'TX', 'US', '75024', '(972) 334.7000', 'FLNAFrito-LayMediaServices@pepsico.com', 'Media Relations', 'http://www.fritolay.com/company/media', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-03-01 04:20:49', '2021-03-01 04:20:49'),
