(673, 'Big Wig Day, Ntl.: January 29', 'United States', '1', '29', '2021', '2021-01-29', '1', '29', '2021', '2021-01-29', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '20', '8', '11', '52', NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Changes', 'Last Friday January', 'https://nationalbigwigday.com', NULL, NULL, 'About National Big Wig Day', NULL, 'The term \'Big Wig\' originated in 1730s Europe. The wealthier you were, the larger the wig you wore. Large or big wigs were then an outward sign of a wealthy important person. In centuries later, the term would come to mean the boss or person in authority.\n\nNational Big Wig Day has less august ambitions. It started as silliness in 2016 and as a way to brighten up a lackluster mid-winter day. It turned into a fundraiser for people struggling with cancer and enduring chemotherapy. Hair loss is one of the symptoms of this. \n\nThe best way to celebrate, sport your favorite wig today and go to the website for the event and choose a charity to donate to including: \n\nAmerican Cancer Society\n\nLook Good Feel Better\n\nDesert Cancer Foundation of Coachella Valley\n\nHospitality House of Boone, North Carolina\n\nUnited Way\n\nEach year sees more charities join. Check the site for the most updated list. ', 'Sharkey Films, LLC', '1833 South Araby Drive ', NULL, 'Palm Springs', 'CA', 'US', '92264', '(949) 294.5695', 'info@nationalbigwigday.com', 'Patty Sharkey', 'https://www.facebook.com/pg/bigwigday/about', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-08-16 15:30:51', '2021-08-16 15:30:51'),
(674, 'Bird Day, Ntl.: January 5', 'United States', '1', '5', '2021', '2021-01-05', '1', '5', '2021', '2021-01-05', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2', '15', '52', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Daily', 'Same', NULL, 'http://www.nationalbirdday.com', NULL, NULL, 'About National Bird Day', NULL, 'Each year for three weeks during the Christmas season the wild bird population (over 9,600 species) of the world is counted.  It is estimated today that twelve percent of these species face extinction. Threats to bird populations include illegal pet trade, disease, pollution, loss of habitat, disease and solar panels and other technological advances.  The Christmas Count, which began in the early 2000s, is the longest running citizen science survey in the world. \n\nNational Bird Day occurs on January 5 each year to mark the conclusion of the Christmas count and bring the focus away from wild birds to those kept in captivity within the United States, most of which are pets and native to other countries. The ultimate goal of National Bird Day is to increase the survival rate and well-being of the world\'s birds through public education and support for conservation.\n\nThis event first ran in 2002. ', 'Born Free USA ', 'P.O. Box 32160', ' ', 'Washington', 'DC', 'US', '20007', '(202) 450.3168', 'press@bornfreeusa.org ', 'Media Relations ', 'http://www.bornfreeusa.org/d6_contact.php', NULL, NULL, NULL, '9023_Bird_Lifecycle_Wheel.pdf', '9023_Bird_Anatomy_Puzzle.pdf', '9023_Go_On_birdwalk.pdf', 'Lifecycle of birds in PDF', 'Teacher Tools: Anatomy of Birds Puzzle', 'Teacher Tools: How to create a bird watching walk', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'LEEP', NULL, 'Pending', '2021-08-16 15:30:51', '2021-08-16 15:30:51'),
